                {
                  "paragraphOrdinal": 2,
                  "paragraphTitle": null,
                  "paragraphSubtitles": [],
                  "paragraphContents": [
                    "Conditional sentences usually have two clauses: the if clause and the result clause. To make second conditional sentences, we use If + simple past and would + base form of the verb."
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "paragraphOrdinal": 3,
                  "paragraphTitle": null,
                  "paragraphSubtitles": [],
                  "paragraphContents": [
                    "With the verb be, we use 'were' instead of 'was'.",
                    "If I were you, I’d vote for the first proposal."
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "paragraphOrdinal": 4,
                  "paragraphTitle": null,
                  "paragraphSubtitles": [],
                  "paragraphContents": [
                    "We use the second conditional to talk about unreal or impossible situations in the present or future."
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "paragraphOrdinal": 5,
                  "paragraphTitle": null,
                  "paragraphSubtitles": [],
                  "paragraphContents": [
                    "If we are not sure of the result, we can use might or could instead of would in the result clause."
                  ]
                }
              ],
